{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512263"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:52:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:52:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11867"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11867"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.04,0.05,0.02,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4467"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103636"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4467"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11867"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86053"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1507"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"3572"},{"type":"tags","id":"4154"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6537"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6568"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7754"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26798"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39145"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43275"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103636"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 31-year-old woman who is currently 9 weeks pregnant and presents to the early pregnancy assessment unit with vaginal bleeding and lower abdominal cramping over the past few hours. She has had 1 previous uncomplicated pregnancy 2 years ago (G2P1). She has no medical history and does not take any medications. Her cervical screening is up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer blood pressure is 80/50 mmHg, pulse rate 55/min, SpO2 99% on room air and temperature 37.4C. On examination, there are no features of peritonism. The uterine fundus is not palpable above the pubic bone. On speculum examination, there is blood in the vaginal canal and tissue coming through an open external cervical os.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntravenous access is established. Blood tests including CBE, group and cross match, EUC, and beta HCG are pending. A point of care transvaginal ultrasound is performed and shows some small retained products of conception.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Incomplete miscarriage with cervical shock","Missed miscarriage with hypovolaemic shock","Complete miscarriage with hypovolaemic shock","Septic miscarriage with septic shock","Inevitable miscarriage with cervical shock"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBleeding in early pregnancy is an extremely common presenting complaint and can be very distressing to women. There are many causes, including miscarriage, ectopic pregnancy, implantation bleeding (in the very early stages of pregnancy), lower genital tract infections and lesions. Of these, miscarriage is one of the most common, with 20-25% of clinically recognised pregnancies resulting in miscarriage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMiscarriage is defined as the loss of a pregnancy before viability (the timing of which differs based off the institution, ranging from 22+6 weeks to 24 weeks). Diagnosis may require a correlation of clinical features plus serial serum hCG and transvaginal ultrasound examinations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMiscarriages are further classified based off the visualisation of production of conception (clinically or on transvaginal ultrasound/TVUS) and the appearance of the cervix. These can be though of as multiple stages across a continium:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ethreatened miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E denotes bleeding from a closed cervical os with or without abdominal pain where TVUS shows an intrauterine gestation sac that either does not meet criteria for miscarriage or demonstrates a viable pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Einevitable miscarriage \u003C/strong\u003Edescribes products of conception being passed or about to pass through an open or bulging cervix\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eincomplete miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E is where products of conception are being passed but there are still intrauterine products (retained products) visible on TVUS, as in this case\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E describes a situation where a previously identified intrauterine pregnancy/gestational sac is no longer seen following complete passage of products of conception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emissed miscarriage \u003C/strong\u003Eis diagnosed on ultrasound in patients who have had no early pregnancy bleeding or pain and have a closed cervix\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eseptic miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E describes any of the above + intrauterine or systemic infection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this question, the patient is likely to be actively passing products of conception through an open cervix, which rules out a threatened or missed miscarriage (where no products have been passed and the cervix is closed). As products are actively being passed, a complete miscarriage has not yet occurred and there are still products of conception within the uterus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore the most correct answer is that this patient is experiencing an\u003Cstrong\u003E incomplete miscarriage with cervical shock\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe second element of this question is regarding to the element of shock. Whilst blood pressure does decrease in the first trimester secondary to a decrease in vascular resistance, her current blood pressure is quite low. Although hypovolaemic shock can occur in the context of bleeding, a tachycardia would be expected, as opposed to a bradycardia - as in this case. In septic shock a temperature and tachycardia would be expected. This combination of hypotension and bradycardia therefore denotes so called \u0027cervical shock\u0027 where the distension of the cervix by the products of conception leads to parasympathetic stimulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Miscarriage type depends on presence, absence or passing of products of conception and whether the cervix is open or closed.","Distension of the cervix can cause hypotension and bradycardia."],"references":["Breeze C. Early pregnancy bleeding. Aust Fam Physician. 2016 May;45(5):283-6. PMID: 27166462. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27166462/","Skubisz C, Khoo A, Leggett C, Simonetti L et al. Bleeding \u0026 Pain in Early Pregnancy. SA Health Perinatal Practice Guidelines. 2021. [Internet]. Accessed on 9 Jan 2025. Available from: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/fead0f004ee4554cb7ecbfd150ce4f37/Bleeding+in+Early+Pregnancy_PPG_v1_3.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026amp;CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-fead0f004ee4554cb7ecbfd150ce4f37-p4bu9Q.","Knez J, Day A, Jurkovic D. Ultrasound imaging in the management of bleeding and pain in early pregnancy. Best Pract Res Clin Obstet Gynaecol. 2014 Jul;28(5):621-36. doi: 10.1016/j.bpobgyn.2014.04.003. Epub 2014 Apr 24. PMID: 24841987. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24841987/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86053"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11867"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86053"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-25T07:50:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-25T07:50:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4467"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103636"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","posit